}}'''''Mermaid Madness''''' is an [[action-adventure game]] developed by Soft Design and published by [[Electric Dreams Software]] for the [[Amstrad CPC]], [[Commodore 64]], and [[ZX Spectrum]] in 1986.

==Gameplay==
The player takes on the role of a 112 year old [[mermaid]] called Myrtle. Myrtle is on a quest to rescue Gordon, a deep sea diver who she has taken a romantic interest in. As Gordon has become trapped in a small cave, Myrtle must find a way to free him before his air runs out. As she travels around the sea bed Myrtle can collect and use a variety of objects. She must also avoid fish and other creatures which can sap her energy. However, energy can be replenished by picking up bottles of [[stout]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.zzap64.co.uk/cgi-bin/displaypage.pl?issue=15&page=38 | title=Redirecting}}</ref>

==Reception==
''Mermaid Madness'' received mostly positive reviews, including scores of 70% from ''[[Amstrad Action]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/amstrad-action-013/Amstrad_Action_013#page/n35/mode/2up/|title=Amstrad Action Issue 013|author=|date=|work=archive.org|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> 37/40 from ''ASM'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/asm_magazine-1986-07/ASM_07_1986#page/n37/mode/1up|title=Aktueller Software Markt (ASM) Magazine (July 1986)|author=|date=July 1986|work=archive.org|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> 7/10 from ''[[Commodore User]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/commodore-user-magazine-35/Commodore_User_Issue_35_1986_Aug#page/n23/mode/1up/|title=Commodore User Magazine Issue 35|author=|date=August 1986|work=archive.org|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> 27/40 from ''[[Computer & Video Games]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/computer-and-videogames-059/ComputerAndVideoGames_059_Sep_1986#page/n25/mode/1up/|title=Computer and Videogames Magazine Issue 059|author=|date=September 1986|work=archive.org|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> 15/20 from ''[[Computer Gamer]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Computer_Gamer_Issue_16_1986-07_Argus_Press_GB#page/n66/mode/1up|title=Computer Gamer - Issue 16 (1986-07)(Argus Press)(GB)|author=|date=July 1986|work=archive.org|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> 66% from ''[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Crash_No._32_1986-09_Newsfield_GB#page/n25/mode/1up/|title=Crash - No. 32 (1986-09)(Newsfield)(GB)|author=|date=September 1986|work=archive.org|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> and 78% from ''[[Zzap!64]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/ZZap64Issue0151986Jul/ZZap_64_Issue_015_1986_Jul#page/n37/mode/1up/|title=ZZap_64_Issue_015_1986_Jul|author=|date=|work=archive.org|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> However, it also received some negative reviews such as 46% from ''Happy Computer''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kultpower.de/archiv/heft_happycomputer_spielesonderheft-2_seite30|title=Kultpower Archiv: Komplettscan Happy Computer Spielesonderheft 2 (1986)|author=|date=|work=kultpower.de|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> and only one star out of five from ''[[Sinclair User]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/sinclair-user-magazine-053/SinclairUser_053_Aug_1986#page/n61/mode/1up/|title=Sinclair User Magazine Issue 053|author=|date=August 1986|work=archive.org|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref>

